Chapter 22: The Drinking Night & Forelhost Breach

PART I: BODY COUNT NIGHT

The Woman

Her day had been good, by the measure she used for days.

She had worked the market bridge from morning bell to dusk — the good spot, the one near the fishery where the smell made people generous to be walking past quickly — and the take had been real coin, enough for once to stop counting it in bread. She had eaten a hot meal at a stall like a person who eats hot meals. And she had carried the rest of it, deliberate and ceremonial, to the Bee and Barb's side window, where Keerava's girl would sell to people the front room wouldn't seat, and bought two whole pints of mead. Two. One for drinking and one for having — for the luxury of a full cup waiting beside a cup you hadn't finished.

She took them to the alley behind the inn, where the kitchen vent breathed warmth over the grate, and she was one pint in and wealthy beyond argument when the side door opened and the nobleman came out.

That was how she filed him. A nobleman, or near enough — young, pale, beautifully kept, with a bottle of something better than hers and two cups, slipping out of the warm room like a man escaping company he could afford to leave. He poured for her without asking and sat against the wall at a respectful distance and listened — actually listened — while the mead and the vent-warmth and the strange, flattering attention loosened a day's worth of words out of her. She talked about the bridge and the fishery smell and the trick of looking pitiful but not contagious. He laughed once, low and real, at the contagious part.

She was thinking, as he leaned in, that the stories were true after all — that the city did sometimes look down and pick somebody up. And the night kept being true. He was attentive in the dark the way he had been attentive over the cups, unhurried, generous, and she had her best night in a year in every sense the phrase will carry — all of it real, all of it hers, paid for in full before the bill came due.

At the height of it, Orion fed.

He was quiet about it, and he was quick, because quick was a kindness and Orion permitted himself kindnesses that didn't cost anything. He held her through it the way you hold something you are being careful with. When it was finished he arranged her against the wall beside her second pint, untouched, still waiting for her.

He was adjusting the lie of her collar — craft, habit, the body found warm in the morning with no marks worth gossip — when footsteps came up the alley and stopped, and a voice behind him said, with clinical dismay:

"Oh, god. That was nasty."

Alfonso had followed the smell. He stood over the woman with the Jagged Crown's case slung at his back and the corroded rapier at his hip, assessing the feed with the professional disappointment of one craftsman reviewing another's joinery. She was not quite gone — the body holding its last business open, a thread of pulse, a flutter. Orion's work, by Orion's standards, finished. By Alfonso's, abandoned on the bench.

He drew the rapier and closed her account. Brisk. Tidy. The mercy of a man for whom death was a process with a correct order of operations and no other significance whatsoever.

Neither of them looked up the stable lane. Neither of them saw the two small figures pressed in the dark of it — Hofgrir's stable boy, out past his hours on an errand that had stopped mattering, and a girl beside him, smaller, quicker, name unknown to anyone in this story. The Warrens taught its children to be furniture when the dangerous people were working. The streets above, it turned out, taught the same curriculum.

The boy ran first.

The Rafter

Alfonso went back inside — invisible, and upward.

His body did not really take drink; mead moved through the colony of him like rain through gravel, and "almost tipsy" was the ceiling of what a night's determined drinking could buy. What proximity to a kill bought instead was a mood: workmanlike, curious, awake. He had a project. He went up the timber of the common room wall and stretched himself along a rafter directly above the heads of Riften's drinking class, a gargoyle taking up a post over the candle-smoke, and there the Carrion Saint practiced scales.

The sickness aura swelled out from him — the radius of rot he carried the way other men carry warmth — and drew back in. Out, to the width of the barroom. In, to the width of his own sleeve. Out further. In tighter. A lung learning its own capacity; a musician finding the edges of an instrument he had owned for years and never properly played. Below him, Keerava poured and patrons laughed and the whole warm room passed in and out of a circle of contagion that expanded and contracted to the rhythm of one monster's breathing, and not one of them ever knew.

Somewhere past the tenth expansion, the practice and the almost-tipsy met in the middle. The aura sagged inward to its resting radius. Alfonso slept, invisible, spread thin along the rafter — a plague dreaming in the roofbeams of the nicest inn in Riften.

The Kiss

At the camp by the canal bridge, while all of this was happening, Varon was having the best and worst night of his adult life.

It had started easily, which should have warned him. Saijah had come back to the cart to check on Mila, and Varon had been there — Varon was always there, still as furniture, the quiet traveler whose road aligned with theirs — and somehow the checking-on had become sitting, and the sitting had become talking. He told her, in Jel, about the marsh birds that sing wrong on purpose to lead hunters away from their nests, and she laughed — actually laughed — and answered in the same tongue, and for an hour the two of them traded the clicking, liquid syllables of their shared childhood like contraband. He was not performing. That was the remarkable thing, the thing he kept noticing sideways: the script had run out somewhere in the first ten minutes and he was still talking. The pain behind his eyes — the daily tincture, the old surgical ache — had gone somewhere and not come back.

It was a good night. It was, by the measure Varon used for nights, the only one.

Which is why he ruined it. Because the Colony had trained him to act on an opening, and her face in the lamplight was an opening, and somewhere in the assassin's architecture a decision got made by the part of him that executed and not the part of him that had been, for one hour, almost a person.

He leaned in to kiss her.

Saijah dodged — a hunter's pure reflex, fast as the arrow at the Ratway door — and was three steps back before either of them understood what had happened, and then she ran. Not walked away. Ran, into the dark along the canal, leaving Varon alone by the cart with the lamplight and the wreckage of the only unscripted hour he could remember, his right hand twitching its old rhythm against his thigh.

She was still walking it off, flushed and furious at nobody she could name, when Davinia found her near the canal door with a body to hide and a brightness like a blade.

The Drunk Adventure

Inside, at the bar, Davinia had just finished the heaviest conversation of her life.

She had sat with Bjorn while he told her about the Pale Pass and the sisters and the forty years, and they had said the things to each other that the night required, and she had left him with his cup and stepped out the canal door because the room had grown too warm and the Crown too quiet, and she wanted air that didn't have anyone's history in it.

What she found in the alley was the woman.

Arranged against the wall. Peaceful, almost — the collar set straight, the second pint standing beside her like a grave-offering — except that Davinia's eyes were not eyes anymore, and through Ismara's sight there was no aura over the body where an aura ought to be, and there were two wounds wearing one story. A feed, neat and practiced. A blade, neater. She stood over the dead woman in the vent-warmth and did the arithmetic the party did now in the place where grief used to go: who did this. Who saw it. What does it cost.

She knew who. Both whos. That was the worst part of the arithmetic — how little of it was a mystery.

What Davinia did next she did with mead in her blood and a thing in her skull that watched her think, and she would examine none of it closely until much later. She went back inside, and she rallied them.

"Get up," she said, bright as a blade. "We're having an adventure."

Not a council. Not a confession. A drunk adventure — her phrase, pitched with a gaiety that fooled nobody and that everybody accepted, because the alternative was to walk out to the alley and stand over the thing and call it by its name, and they were none of them drunk enough for that and all of them too drunk for it. Saijah came — glad, in the moment, of anything that wasn't the canal-side dark and the thing that had almost happened at the cart. Saijah, who had held Mila's hand through the Warrens, who carried Kynareth's silence like a stone — Saijah helped. The weights, the canal, the dark water doing what dark water does. The party of chartered Wardens of the realm disposed of a murdered beggar with the smooth cooperation of people who had, somewhere along the road from Solitude, acquired this as a skill the way other companies acquire siegecraft.

Which left the witnesses. Because there had been witnesses — Davinia had found the scuff-marks in the lane, child-sized, two sets, one of them running. And runners have destinations.

The Stables

Hofgrir's stables sat against the city wall, warm with animal dark, and the boy was in it.

He had run home, because home was where the horses were and the horses were the only things in his day that had never frightened him. He was doing his night-work badly with shaking hands — water pails, straw, the thousand small motions of a job he could do asleep — when the lantern-light crossed the yard, and he looked up, and he knew them.

It was all over his face. The alley. The pale lord with the cups. The grey one who smelled like deep water and stabbed like he was trimming a wick. The boy stood in the stall beside a big bay mare with a pail in his hands, and he knew them, and they watched him know them, and the night narrowed to a point.

Nobody had decided anything yet. That mattered afterward, to some of them — that there had been a moment where the night could have gone another way, a bribe, a threat, a lie, anything. The moment was still open when Alfonso solved it.

He cast Fury. Not at the boy.

At the mare.

The spell took the animal the way a spark takes dry grass. Half a ton of gentle, stall-broken horse came apart from itself in a single convulsion — ears flat, eyes white round the rim, the scream that horses save for fire and wolves — and the boy was between her and the gate. He had spent his whole short life learning to read horses and there was nothing in this one left to read; the magic had emptied her out and filled her with one instruction. She spun in the stall and her iron-shod weight went over him and through him, and the pail rang off the boards, and it was finished before any of the people watching had settled whether they were going to allow it.

The spell faded on its own schedule. The mare stood trembling over what she had done, foam at her mouth, returned to herself with blood on her feathered hooves and no way to understand it. Stables kill boys every year in exactly this shape. Hofgrir would grieve, and blame himself, and never once think the word murder, because horses are dangerous and boys are careless and the world is full of accidents that look precisely like this.

Alfonso looked at his work and found it efficient.

What he did not find — what none of them found, because the spell that swept the stable's shadows slid across her mind and failed, the one roll of the night that mattered most quietly — was the girl.

She was in the hayloft, where she had gone because the boy had told her to go up while he kept watch below, and she had watched the whole of it through the gap in the boards: the lanterns crossing the yard, the gesture from the grey one's hand, the mare's scream, the boy — her friend, her only — going down under the hooves. She watched the heroes of Riften, the Lanterns whose names were thanked on notices three streets away, stand in the lamplight over a dead child and a ruined horse and feel nothing she could see from above except relief.

She did not make a sound. The Warrens curriculum, again: some dangers announce themselves, and some smile, and some simply tidy up.

They left without ever knowing what they were leaving in the loft.

Grelod

The Bee and Barb at the late hour had thinned to its serious drinkers, and at the bar, improbably, sat Grelod the Kind.

Riften loved her. That has to be understood the way Riften understood it: Grelod ran Honorhall, fed the city's orphans on charity and patience, and had done so for thirty years with the public bearing of everyone's stern, devoted grandmother. She drank like a woman with a reputation to maintain — small sips, warm chuckles, a hand laid briefly on the forearm of the big grey-bearded carter who had taken the stool beside her.

And Bjorn — two cups past his usual stopping point, with Mila checked on twice and asleep on the cart under three blankets and the spare oilskin — was flirting back.

He told her the one about the slaughterfish and the wedding ring. She laughed in the right places, and meant at least some of it. He liked her laugh. He liked the ordinariness of her, the talk of children and budgets and the price of flour, the whole warm fiction of a woman who had given her life to keeping little ones safe — because that fiction was the exact shape of the hole in Bjorn, and for a quarter of an hour at the end of a terrible hidden night, the old man got to sit in candlelight and feel like a person with an ordinary life, talking to a person with a kind one.

Across the room, Alfonso — retrieved from his rafter, restored to the company of the living, smelling faintly of altitude — watched the two of them with his head tilted, and the idea assembled itself in him with the same clean logic as the mare.

He knew what Grelod was. Orion's intelligence from the Ratway had been thorough: the beatings, the starvings, the compliant children sold quietly into Maven's pipelines. A monster with a city for a costume. And here she sat, in range, beside the fastest hands in the party. Fury, on Grelod, now. Let the costume come apart in public. Let Bjorn — strong, close, already half-charmed — be the one who had to put her down when she turned. Two problems, one spell, and the old man does the work and never has to know he was aimed.

He was already composing the gesture when Davinia's hand closed on his wrist.

She had watched him watch them. She knew the tilt of that head. And she talked him down the only way Alfonso could be talked down — not with mercy, which bought nothing in his ledger, but with arithmetic: a crowded bar. A hundred witnesses. A beloved woman coming apart in public twenty feet from the city's favorite carter, on a night when there was already a body in the canal and a dead boy in the stables, in a city run by a woman who counted everything. The party was one bad hour from losing all of it — the charter, the cover, the celebrated name on the notices — and Grelod's account, Davinia said, would keep. It was not going anywhere. Neither was Honorhall.

Alfonso heard the part of it that was numbers. The gesture stayed uncomposed. Grelod finished her drink, patted Bjorn's arm, told him to come by the orphanage sometime and see the children's garden, and went home unaware of how nearly the room had rearranged itself around her.

The party slept. Above the canal door, the rafter held the memory of its plague. In the hayloft, a girl sat with her back against the boards and her knees against her chest and did not sleep at all.

PART II: THE MORNING

The Debate

The morning brought cold fog off the lake, as mornings in Riften do, and the three fires onto the breakfast table with the bread.

They had been arriving all week, the fires, each with its own courier. The Stormcloak soldier upstairs, dying in increments of the plague that had hollowed out Galmar's army — begging Windhelm's case every time Davinia passed his door, in Galmar's name, if you have any honor left. Klimmek at the bar most mornings now, drinking through what he had seen on the 7,000 Steps — the Waystones bleeding black sap, the grey robes with faces of horn and fire, the air gone wrong like time was bending — and Saijah's migraine agreeing with him, the spike behind her left eye swung southwest and pointing like a held compass at the Throat of the World. And folded into the cart's false bottom, an old man with three books and thirty years of preparation, asking in his cracked, patient voice for a stone tablet from a barrow above Riverwood, because without it everything else we might do is a reaction, not a strategy.

The debate ran the length of breakfast and then some.

Windhelm pulled at Davinia, and pulled hard — though only she could feel the full depth of the hooks in it, the lie about the Crown sitting under Galmar's trust like a stone under snow. The plague was killing the man who called her his friend's daughter, and the plague was theirs. She did not say that second part at the table. It sat with her anyway.

Ivarstead pulled at Saijah with the simple honesty of pain. The mountain was the source. The signature she had tracked since Thornheart Grove had climbed the most sacred stair in Skyrim and was bleeding the stones of it, and every hour the party sat in Riften the spike behind her eye repeated its one instruction.

The vote split, and split again. Windhelm; Ivarstead. Ivarstead; Windhelm. Bjorn kept the tally out of it and the stew moving.

Bleak Falls Barrow was not discussed. Esbern's commission — the map of every dragon grave in Skyrim, the key to fighting the war instead of surviving it — sat at the bottom of the pile, unconsidered. It was the cold fire. Nobody in it was dying on a timer. The old man heard the debate from the cart's false bottom, all of it, and said nothing, and reorganized his three books.

What broke the tie was not honor, and not pain. It was gold, and a debt of answers.

Maven Black-Briar's bounty still stood open: five thousand septims to name whoever had poisoned her meadery and nearly killed her son. The party knew more than Maven did — knew the contamination was a refined plague strain, knew the work was signed in its own way — and the signature pointed up the mountain southeast of the city, to a fortress above the lake where the trail of the rival alchemist began. Forelhost. The source. Half a day's climb from the gates.

And Alfonso wanted it the way a duelist wants the man who has been forging his signature.

He had read the strain at the meadery. It was his work — his own plague, harvested from somewhere and handed to a stranger's refinement, made cleaner and colder and more obedient, and sent back into the world wearing his style like a stolen coat. Somewhere up that mountain was an alchemist named Antoine, last heir of a lineage that had been perfecting one inheritance for four thousand years, who had looked at the living rot of Peryite's chosen and decided he could improve it. Peryite's own approval had radiated, faintly, damnably, toward the cleaner work. That could not stand. None of them said this at the table either, but it was the largest thing on it.

Settle the bounty. Take the answers. Burn the rival's garden. Then choose a fire.

Forelhost first.

PART III: THE BREACH

The Killing Field

The fortress announced itself the way Forelhost announced everything — with arithmetic.

It sat above the lake at the end of a switchback climb, walls still square after forty centuries, and its outer court was garrisoned by the dead in numbers that made the head count meaningless somewhere past the first dozen. Skeletal defenders, ranked and patient, holding overlapping fields of fire with the mechanical contentment of things that have one instruction and eternity to follow it. A frontal approach was a tax. The party declined to pay it.

They paid in conjuring instead. The atronach went in at the western wall, burning and loud and magnificently expendable, and the garrison turned toward it with a single motion, like grass bending under one wind. The party crossed the court through the gap the distraction opened — quick, low, unglorious — and were through the inner doors before the atronach finished dying its rented death. Behind them the skeletons returned to their posts and the field resumed its four-thousand-year arrangement, minus nothing it would miss.

The Ossuary

The ossuary was where Forelhost stopped being a ruin and started being a facility.

Bone-drawers lined the walls in catalogued ranks — a family's worth of ancestors filed like correspondence — and the chamber's center held a platform scrubbed to a sterility that had no business existing in a tomb. No dust. No webs. Air that moved through the room on some ancient ventilation schedule and left it cleaner than a temple. Whoever worked here had needs that the dead do not have.

Alfonso could not cross it.

He tried — stepped to the threshold of the sterile field the way he stepped toward most barriers, with proprietary impatience — and the platform's old wardwork refused him the way a wound refuses dirt. The field existed to keep foreign biology out of the workspace, and Alfonso was foreign biology in a coat. He stood at its edge with the static of rejection crawling over him, and after a moment he stepped back and waved the others through with a courtier's irony that did not entirely cover the fact of what had just been demonstrated. The fortress had built a room that he, specifically, was not clean enough to enter — wardwork four thousand years old, refusing him as if it had been waiting for him. None of them thought harder about it than that. Later, all of them would.

Davinia crossed the platform reading the room the way she read everything now — through Ismara's eyes, the inscriptions opening their intent to her without troubling to be translated, the old containment channels in the stone lit up like veins. The room was a workspace for handling something that must not escape.

The room, in its small way, read her back.

The exposure was light. A breath of the place; a kiss of what it kept. Forelhost Strain 1.0 — the refined plague, the meadery poison, Antoine's signature — entered her the way fine dust enters a house, and found in her precisely the kind of address such things remember: a body already humming with the Crown's magical presence, a host marked out from the herd. She felt almost nothing. A warmth. A passing wrongness. She noted it the way she noted most damage now — as information, filed — and did not yet know she was carrying a clock.

They found the journals in the ossuary, among the drawers and the labels in a dead family's hand, and they read them where they stood. The voice in the pages was meticulous, joyless, and very young once — Antoine, the last of the line, writing to no one across years of solitary refinement. And threaded through the chemistry, unmistakably, was a subject: a study of Alfonso himself. His methods. His synthesis. His habits of mind, deduced from his work the way a tracker deduces the animal from the print, annotated with the exacting admiration of a rival who had decided to know his enemy down to the bone.

Alfonso read his own profile with the Crown's case on his back and his lip curling.

"This guy thinks he fucking knows me," he said, and dropped the journal back on its shelf.

The party took what the pages offered — the shape of the man, the scale of the inheritance, the unsettling competence — and went deeper. The question of whether Antoine knew him would keep. It had, as it turned out, about two hours left to keep.

The Refinery

The refinery was a working alchemist's floor — extraction fields humming between the pillars, cage-traps at the thresholds that the party learned to read and walk around, vats holding their temperatures for a master who had stepped out. And its library was the prize: texts annotated mid-use, diagrams corrected in a cramped marginal hand, the accumulated shorthand of forty centuries of one family talking to itself about one subject.

The translation took an hour, and the hour belonged to Davinia.

She read with her hand resting on each page, relaying — not the words, which were in three languages and two ciphers, but the intent beneath them, which her eyes drank without effort. The party stood watch while she worked. Saijah on the door. Orion in whatever shadow held the best sightlines. The hour passed in the scratch of Davinia's notes and the hum of the fields.

It was Ismara who found the hidden journal.

The Crown had been quiet company all day — it was always quiet company now, helpful and warm and almost kind, which was its own category of alarming that Davinia had stopped examining. And then, as her gaze crossed Antoine's personal workstation, the voice arrived in her skull with the dry, proprietary disapproval of a senior researcher touring a junior's lab.

The bench is poorly organized. The reagent staging is wasteful — look, he stages acids beside reductants, the boy is begging for an accident. And the left rear leg is shimmed. With a book. There, under the leg — someone has hidden a thing where only a person who cares about furniture would ever look.

Davinia knelt. The shim was a journal, bound small, wedged spine-out beneath the bench leg. It was exactly what Ismara said it was, and it held exactly what such a hiding place promised: the pages Antoine kept from his own family record.

The help had cost nothing. It had asked nothing. It had arrived wrapped in wit, and it was gone again as soon as it was spent, leaving only the small, growing fact that the thing in Davinia's head was useful, and pleasant, and on her side. That was all. That was always all, lately.

The hidden pages gave them the password. At the containment threshold — a door built like a vault against everything Forelhost feared letting out — Davinia spoke a dead family's countersign, and the door, recognizing its own household's words, opened without resistance and let the intruders in.

The Laboratory

Rahgot's sarcophagus stood open.

That was the first thing the room told them, and it told them carelessly, as if the information were minor. The great stone lid was shoved aside — not toppled, not broken, moved, by something with the strength to be unhurried about it — and the dust on the floor recorded a single departure: steps down from the dais, across the chamber, out. A Dragon Priest had risen from this box, walked through his descendant's laboratory, and left on his own schedule. The lab had gone on working without him. The vats held their temperatures. The machinery hummed its maintenance hum. Whatever Rahgot was now, he had not needed to wreck anything on his way out, and somehow that was worse.

And between the workstations and the empty stone, in a crescent bed of dark soil that pulsed with a slow, wet rhythm of its own, grew the garden.

The Tears of Rahgot. Antoine's binding agent — the keystone of the next strain, the component his journals circled and circled — growing in tended rows like any herb bed, fat dark blooms nodding over soil that moved like something breathing under a blanket. The sight of it assembled the whole picture: the meadery had been a field test. This was the farm.

They worked the room before they touched the garden. Against the far wall stood an apparatus built around relics of the Breaker — the processing rig assembled to receive Ulag's harvest, the machinery by which Antoine meant to draw the living quality of Alfonso's strain out of the one infected vessel he controlled. The party wrecked it. Thoroughly, methodically, with the satisfaction of people pulling teeth out of a plan they had finally understood.

And Davinia found the alcove.

Her eyes caught it where mortal eyes had nothing to catch — a seam in the stonework with intent behind it, a press-plate worked into the masonry at hip height. She pressed. The wall opened on a niche that the Wizard Sight had already half-read through the rock, and inside, alone on a stand, sat the Forelhost Alchemy Codex: the family's master text, four thousand years of one lineage's accumulated craft, the book every journal in the fortress had been a footnote to. She lifted it out. It was heavier than a book that size should be, the way some inheritances are.

Then it was the garden's turn. Alfonso looked at his rival's crop for a long moment.

Then he activated Ancestral Wrath — the fire of his line wrapping his hands in a corona of green-white heat — and reached down into the crescent to gather the Tears and burn them out of the world.

The ceiling answered him.

The Cage

The trap had been built by a man who had studied exactly one target, and it had been built well. This guy thinks he fucking knows me, Alfonso had said, two hours and one floor ago. The ceiling was Antoine's reply.

The cage came down faster than reflex — a sealed lattice of pale alloy and layered wardwork, dropping from a housing none of them had read as anything but ceiling, swallowing Alfonso and the whole crescent of soil together. Its seams met the floor with a sound like a ledger closing. Inside, runes woke along every bar in sequence, and somewhere above, machinery began counting.

Davinia moved before the count was audible. The mace went up on the Wizard Hand's strength — Ismara's ice architecture driving it like a piston — and struck the cage's underside at the joint of bar and floor-seam. The whole structure jumped. An inch of air opened between lattice and stone. An inch of possibility.

Alfonso did the rest from inside, and he did it like a man signing his name.

Wall of Frost, cast downward into the gap — but built on the somatic grammar with one deliberate component seated in the casting like a keystone: STABILIZE. The ice bloomed under the bars and lifted, and what it lifted onto was not ordinary frost. Stabilized ice resists entropy. Heat would not soften it. Dispel would slide off it. Time itself would have to queue. The cage rose on its frozen wedge and sat there, jacked crooked off its seating, propped a foot out of true on a block of ice engineered to outlast the machine it was defeating.

And Alfonso went for the gap.

He was fast — he had always been fast when it counted, the rot-slick economy of a body that did not waste motion on being alive — and the gap under the lifted bars was almost wide enough, and the timer was almost long enough, and he was almost out. Shoulders through. The Crown's case scraping the bar above him. One hand on free stone.

The timer had never been negotiable. Antoine built redundancies; the journals had said so in six different ways.

The sterilization field filled the cage's volume in one white, soundless pulse, and caught him at the threshold — half-born from his rival's trap, one hand in the open air. It was a ward that killed foreign biology. All of it. Total, indiscriminate, instant: the engineer's answer to the problem of safely handling a man who was himself a contagion.

It worked. It worked completely.

It killed every foreign cell in the cage — and every cell of Alfonso was foreign. The body that had walked out of Morrowind, the grey hands that had stirred a thousand cures and ten thousand poisons, the face that had knelt to Mila in a tunnel and promised her the fire would not touch her — all of it was pathogen, all the way through, a colony wearing a man's shape, and the field unmade it the way bleach unmakes a culture. There was no wound. There was no cry. The robes settled, empty, into the dark soil, and the Jagged Crown — cased, carried, never once worn — came down with them and clattered to the cage floor and lay still.

The corroded rapier dropped flat beside it. And nothing about the rapier changed at all.

Because nothing had fled to it. There had been nothing in the body to flee.

The soul of Alfonso Duet had lived in that iron since the night at the camp between Mzinchaleft and Riften — the night he had worked an enchantment that demanded a soul gem he did not have, and had solved the absence the way Forelhost itself had once solved it with four thousand sacrifices: he used himself. He had poured his own existence down into his family's iron dagger, and the dagger, receiving the whole weight of a living soul, had transmuted under it — drawn itself out long and lethal, reshaped around what it now contained, dagger into rapier, heirloom into reliquary. Everything that had walked and talked and brewed and schemed since that night — everything the party had traveled with, argued with, trusted at their backs — had been the iron's dream of the man, a projection grown around an anchor and worn like a remembered coat.

The sterilization field had not killed Alfonso. It had burned away the picture of him, and left the original lying on the cage floor: a corroded blade under a wedge of its own unmeltable ice — intact, awake, and under no obligation whatsoever to grow the picture back.

Across the laboratory, with a hydraulic patience that was almost comic, Antoine's extraction arm unfolded from its housing and extended toward the cage along its programmed track. This was the trap's whole purpose — the harvest. Catch the plague-lord, sterilize the volume, and draw off the residue of the one thing Antoine's genius could not synthesize: the living quality of Alfonso's work. The arm reached the end of its track, flexed its collector head at the limit of its tolerances, and closed on air.

The cage was a foot out of position, jacked crooked on a block of stabilized ice that the machine's designer had never imagined, because the machine's designer had never imagined the target helping to lift his own trap.

The collector cycled once, found nothing, registered nothing, and retracted.

The trap had executed perfectly, in every particular, and collected exactly nothing. Somewhere on the road north, its maker did not yet know that the finest piece of engineering of his life had just been beaten by a shim of ice and a dead man's furniture-sense — or that the sample he had built it all to take was lying on the cage floor in plain sight, wearing the one shape no syringe was ever designed to draw from.

The Draugr

The wall alcoves opened on the same circuit as the arm. Antoine built redundancies.

They came out wrong, and the wrongness was the point of them: False Draugr — the laboratory's imitations of the Dragon Cult's ancient soldiery, Antoine's craft mimicking Ulag's designs, obedient and tireless and empty. Four of them, then a fifth, a sixth, deploying from the alcoves with weapons up and the lab's pale light sliding off the wet seams of their construction. The party had marked the alcoves on the way in and elected, in the way of parties with richer problems, to leave them for later.

Later had arrived. All of it at once, at full strength, in formation.

Davinia set her feet beside the displaced cage, mace in the Wizard Hand, the Crown humming with something that was not quite excitement. Saijah's bow came around, the predator senses mapping six gaits, six weights, six wrongnesses in the time it took to draw. Orion was no longer where he had been standing.

And on the floor of the cage, under ice that would not melt, behind bars that no longer mattered, the corroded rapier lay among the empty robes with four thousand years of patience available to it — no body, no haste, and no intention, yet, of explaining itself to anyone.

The False Draugr crossed the laboratory floor in step, and the night held its breath there — on the drawn arrow, on the raised mace, on the first clash that had not yet come.

